<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="53" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1440,1327,1973]" box="[151,1375,1327,1354]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,295,1327,1353]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Etymology:</emphasis>
—specific epithet refers to the occurrence of the new species in alpine, high elevation lakes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1440,1327,1973]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Potapova &amp; Enache" authorityYear="2013" box="[198,491,1365,1391]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Psammothidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="alpinum">
<emphasis box="[198,491,1365,1391]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Psammothidium alpinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Germain 1957: 85) Bukhtiyarova et Round (1996: 9)" authorityName="Bukhtiyarova et Round" authorityPageNumber="9" authorityYear="1996" baseAuthorityName="Germain" baseAuthorityPageNumber="85" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[648,1405,1365,1392]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Psammothidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="bioretii">
<emphasis box="[648,762,1365,1391]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">P. bioretii</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Germain, H." box="[779,996,1366,1392]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" pagination="85 - 86" refId="ref4591" refString="Germain, H. (1957) Achnanthes bioreti n. sp., diatomee nouvelle. Bulletin de la Societe Botanique de France 104 (suppl.): 85 - 86." type="journal article" year="1957">Germain 1957: 85</bibRefCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation author="Bukhtiyarova, L. &amp; Round, F. E." box="[1013,1405,1366,1392]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" pagination="1 - 30" refId="ref4414" refString="Bukhtiyarova, L. &amp; Round, F. E. (1996) Revision of the genus Achnanthes sensu lato section Marginulatae Bukht. Sect. nov. of Achnanthidium Kutz. Diatom Research 11: 1 - 30. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 0269249 X. 1996.9705361" type="journal article" year="1996">Bukhtiyarova et Round (1996: 9)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in valve size and possession of relatively coarse areolae. It differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bukhtiyarova et Round" authorityYear="1996" baseAuthorityName="Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[999,1117,1404,1430]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Psammothidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="bioretii">
<emphasis box="[999,1117,1404,1430]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">P. bioretii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having more elongate, linear-elliptical valve shape with nearly parallel sides, and a straight central sternum (versus diagonal in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bukhtiyarova et Round" authorityYear="1996" baseAuthorityName="Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1957" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Psammothidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="bioretii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">P. bioretii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). In SEM (
<figureCitation box="[374,512,1483,1509]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–44" captionStartId="6.[151,258,1909,1931]" captionTargetBox="[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetId="figure-188@6.[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 40–44: Psammothidium alpinum sp. nov., SEM. Figs 40–42. Type material, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA019 Fig. 40. External view of raphe valve. Fig. 41. Internal view of raphe valve. Fig. 42. External view of rapheless valve. Fig. 43. Internal view of rapheless valve, Hidden Lake NOCA, sample ANSP WACA018. Fig. 44. Areolae on the internal surface of the valve, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA001. Scale bars = 1 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5085475" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5085475/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Figs 40–44</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Potapova &amp; Enache" authorityYear="2013" box="[535,662,1482,1508]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Psammothidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="alpinum">
<emphasis box="[535,662,1482,1508]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">P. alpinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
displays a characteristic doublet of smaller areolae at the valve/ mantle junction and around the mantle (
<figureCitation box="[613,749,1521,1547]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–44" captionStartId="6.[151,258,1909,1931]" captionTargetBox="[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetId="figure-188@6.[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 40–44: Psammothidium alpinum sp. nov., SEM. Figs 40–42. Type material, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA019 Fig. 40. External view of raphe valve. Fig. 41. Internal view of raphe valve. Fig. 42. External view of rapheless valve. Fig. 43. Internal view of rapheless valve, Hidden Lake NOCA, sample ANSP WACA018. Fig. 44. Areolae on the internal surface of the valve, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA001. Scale bars = 1 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5085475" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5085475/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Figs 40, 42</figureCitation>
). On raphe valves, the central area nearly reaches the valve margin and is bounded by 4–8 short striae. The raphe has characteristic hook-like widely spaced proximal endings (
<figureCitation box="[257,336,1598,1624]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–44" captionStartId="6.[151,258,1909,1931]" captionTargetBox="[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetId="figure-188@6.[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 40–44: Psammothidium alpinum sp. nov., SEM. Figs 40–42. Type material, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA019 Fig. 40. External view of raphe valve. Fig. 41. Internal view of raphe valve. Fig. 42. External view of rapheless valve. Fig. 43. Internal view of rapheless valve, Hidden Lake NOCA, sample ANSP WACA018. Fig. 44. Areolae on the internal surface of the valve, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA001. Scale bars = 1 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5085475" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5085475/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Fig 40</figureCitation>
) that deflect in the same direction externally (
<figureCitation box="[872,958,1598,1624]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–44" captionStartId="6.[151,258,1909,1931]" captionTargetBox="[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetId="figure-188@6.[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 40–44: Psammothidium alpinum sp. nov., SEM. Figs 40–42. Type material, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA019 Fig. 40. External view of raphe valve. Fig. 41. Internal view of raphe valve. Fig. 42. External view of rapheless valve. Fig. 43. Internal view of rapheless valve, Hidden Lake NOCA, sample ANSP WACA018. Fig. 44. Areolae on the internal surface of the valve, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA001. Scale bars = 1 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5085475" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5085475/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
) and opposite internally (
<figureCitation box="[1256,1344,1598,1624]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–44" captionStartId="6.[151,258,1909,1931]" captionTargetBox="[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetId="figure-188@6.[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 40–44: Psammothidium alpinum sp. nov., SEM. Figs 40–42. Type material, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA019 Fig. 40. External view of raphe valve. Fig. 41. Internal view of raphe valve. Fig. 42. External view of rapheless valve. Fig. 43. Internal view of rapheless valve, Hidden Lake NOCA, sample ANSP WACA018. Fig. 44. Areolae on the internal surface of the valve, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA001. Scale bars = 1 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5085475" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5085475/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
). While 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bukhtiyarova et Round" authorityYear="1996" baseAuthorityName="Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[151,266,1636,1662]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Psammothidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="bioretii">
<emphasis box="[151,266,1636,1662]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">P. bioretii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has terminal raphe fissures curved to opposite sides, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Potapova &amp; Enache" authorityYear="2013" box="[904,1031,1636,1662]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Psammothidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="alpinum">
<emphasis box="[904,1031,1636,1662]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">P. alpinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks terminal fissures, and distal external raphe endings are drop-shaped and do not expand beyond the last stria (
<figureCitation box="[1085,1172,1676,1702]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–44" captionStartId="6.[151,258,1909,1931]" captionTargetBox="[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetId="figure-188@6.[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 40–44: Psammothidium alpinum sp. nov., SEM. Figs 40–42. Type material, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA019 Fig. 40. External view of raphe valve. Fig. 41. Internal view of raphe valve. Fig. 42. External view of rapheless valve. Fig. 43. Internal view of rapheless valve, Hidden Lake NOCA, sample ANSP WACA018. Fig. 44. Areolae on the internal surface of the valve, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA001. Scale bars = 1 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5085475" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5085475/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
). Similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bukhtiyarova et Round" authorityYear="1996" baseAuthorityName="Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[1316,1428,1675,1701]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Psammothidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="bioretii">
<emphasis box="[1316,1428,1675,1701]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">P. bioretii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Potapova &amp; Enache" authorityYear="2013" box="[151,278,1714,1740]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Psammothidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="alpinum">
<emphasis box="[151,278,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">P. alpinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has coarse, round areolae visible in LM; a row of coarser areolae border the sternum and central area in LM (
<figureCitation box="[298,430,1753,1779]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–21" captionStartId="3.[151,259,1929,1951]" captionTargetBox="[187,1403,537,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-233@3.[187,1404,537,1903]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–21: LM micrographs of Psammothidium species from Snow Lake, Washington Cascades. Figs 1–8. Psammothidium lacustre sp. nov. Figs 1–2. Holotype specimen, slide ANSP GC64860. Figs 9–21. Psammothidium alpinum sp. nov. Figs 9–10. Holotype specimen, slide ANSP GC64862. Scale bar = 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5085463" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5085463/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Figs 10, 11</figureCitation>
) and a double row of finer areolae bordering the valve face-mantle junction is visible in SEM (
<figureCitation box="[260,401,1792,1818]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–44" captionStartId="6.[151,258,1909,1931]" captionTargetBox="[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetId="figure-188@6.[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 40–44: Psammothidium alpinum sp. nov., SEM. Figs 40–42. Type material, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA019 Fig. 40. External view of raphe valve. Fig. 41. Internal view of raphe valve. Fig. 42. External view of rapheless valve. Fig. 43. Internal view of rapheless valve, Hidden Lake NOCA, sample ANSP WACA018. Fig. 44. Areolae on the internal surface of the valve, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA001. Scale bars = 1 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5085475" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5085475/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Figs 40, 42</figureCitation>
). Short intercalary striae are present along the valve margin and expand on the mantle (
<figureCitation box="[159,294,1830,1856]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–44" captionStartId="6.[151,258,1909,1931]" captionTargetBox="[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetId="figure-188@6.[372,1214,1010,1886]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 40–44: Psammothidium alpinum sp. nov., SEM. Figs 40–42. Type material, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA019 Fig. 40. External view of raphe valve. Fig. 41. Internal view of raphe valve. Fig. 42. External view of rapheless valve. Fig. 43. Internal view of rapheless valve, Hidden Lake NOCA, sample ANSP WACA018. Fig. 44. Areolae on the internal surface of the valve, Snow Lake, sample ANSP WACA001. Scale bars = 1 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5085475" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5085475/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Figs 41, 43</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Potapova &amp; Enache" authorityYear="2013" box="[314,606,1829,1855]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Psammothidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="alpinum">
<emphasis box="[314,606,1829,1855]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Psammothidium alpinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has similar valve shape as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hohn et Hellerman 1963: 273) Lange-Bertalot (1999: 285)" authorityName="Lange-Bertalot" authorityPageNumber="285" authorityYear="1999" baseAuthorityName="Hohn et Hellerman" baseAuthorityPageNumber="273" baseAuthorityYear="1963" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Psammothidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="chlidanos">
<emphasis box="[921,1062,1829,1855]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">P. chlidanos</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hohn, M. H. &amp; Hellerman, J." box="[1078,1427,1830,1856]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" pagination="250 - 329" refId="ref4625" refString="Hohn, M. H. &amp; Hellerman, J. (1963) Taxonomy and structure of diatom populations from three eastern North American rivers. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society 82: 250 - 329. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.2307 / 3223932" type="journal article" year="1963">Hohn et Hellerman 1963: 273</bibRefCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation author="Lange-Bertalot, H." box="[151,470,1869,1895]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" pagination="276 - 289" refId="ref4708" refString="Lange-Bertalot, H. (1999) Neue Kombinationen von Taxa aus Achnanthes Bory (sensu lato). Iconographia Diatomologica 6: 276 - 289." type="journal article" year="1999">Lange-Bertalot (1999: 285)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
but it can be easily distinguished by its coarser striae and areolae visible in LM.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1440,1327,1973]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Potapova &amp; Enache" authorityYear="2013" box="[198,324,1907,1934]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Psammothidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="alpinum">
<emphasis box="[198,213,1908,1933]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[228,324,1907,1933]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">alpinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was present in Hidden Lake NOCA (bottom sample, 2% relative abundance) and very rare in top samples from Snow and Stiletto lakes.
</paragraph>
